egal\nliquor business will be Investigated\nIn the very near future. It Is the plan\nof Sheriff Barker and tho county\ncommissioners to bring nil bootleg\ngors to answer to tho law.\nOPTIMISTIC OVER\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nManager of Hardware Store Bejleves\nLogan Will Forge To the Front\nThis 8ummer\nManager W. R. Sloan of the' La\nFount Hardware Company has Just\n.i jetiini.from a trip to Denver, Kun\nm aaa City and St. 'Louis where he,\nwent for the special mission ot at\ntending a course in good salesmanship\ngiven by one of the large manufac\nturers from which his company pur\nChases considerable hardware. Mr.\nSloan was seen yesterday regarding\nthe purpose of his trip and what ho\nobserved In tho east. Ho says there\nis optimism everywhere In tho cast\nSERENADE\nLOGAN\nPARTIES\nWellsvllle People Bring Back Memor\nies of the Happy Past. An\nEnjoyable Time Had\nOn Tuesday night tho homes of Lor\nenzo Hansen, S, B. Mltton, Mrs. Ag\nnes Phillips and Mrs. Sarah J. Park\nof Logan wero besieged by a number\nof their old time friends from Wolls\nvlllo, headed by William S. Popplo\nton and Lorenzo Thorpe, who treated\ntheir Logan friends to a midnight\nserenade, which awakened fond mem-,\norles ot happy days long since past.\nOld tlmo Incidents wero tho burden\not conversation, and a very 'ngroca\nbio tlmo was onjoyed until tho small\nhours of tho morning. Wellsvllllans,\ncome again!\nTho Ballard Camp of tho Daugh-iV-\n-T-ifisof tho Pioneers will meet on\nas to tho futuro business outlook ov\ner the country. And what Is more,\nsaid Mr. Sloan, I believe that Logan\nwill have one of the most prosperous\nseasons in 1914 that she has ever\nhad. I can see that the farmers ar\nlooking for big crops since we have\nhad such a favorable\" winter. The\nbuilders are beaming over with\nsmiles on account of tho contracts\nthey havo ahead. All this activity can\nnot come without bringing with It\nprosperity and I believe Logan and\nCache valley will see. many wonder\nful improvements during the coming\nseason and as a consequence It is\ncertain to bring prosperity to thoso\nwho take advantage of the conditions.\nFriday February 20 at 3 o'clock at\nthe residonco of Mrs. Jtf. J. Watklns\n131 South Third West. A good atten\ndance is desired.\nADVERTI8ED LETTERS\nLogan, Feb. 17, 1914.\nAnderson Bros.\nAnderson, Harry.\nBerg, O. A.\nChrlstensen, Miss Olga.\nCrookston, W. C.\nLovander, William. -i\nMorris, Edward N.\nMorford, Miss Rao.\nPatterson, Peter.\nWard, Ray.\nWright,' Coulson.\nWllmott, Mrs. L.\nJoseph Odoll, Postmaster.\nMr. and Mrs. E. M. Wright will\nbe In Logan Saturday. Mr. Wright\nrecently graduated from tho Ann Ar\nbor Law School whoro ho has been\nstudying for tho past two years and\na half, Including both summer and\nwinter terms. Tlieao peoplo are\nnow visiting In Montpollor and Po\ncatollo boforo making a visit with\nLogan friends.\nBasketball\nCame Friday\nJensen's Team Will Play the C. S. A.\nTeam the Southern Idaho\nChampion\nThe B. Y. College will moot the\nfast C. S, Academy team, champions\nof southern Idaho on Friday after\nnoon, Fobruary 20 at 4 p. m. Tho\nB. Y. College llnoup will tncludo tho\nmon who holpod defeat tho Aggies\nlast Friday night. Coa'ch Jensen\nfeels that thoy will mako a good\nshowing.\nSUGAR BEET SEED\nCLEANING MACHINE\nThe department of agronomy of tho\nAgricultural Collego has recently had\nconstructed a machine for cleaning\nsugar beet seed on a commercial,\nscale.\nOne ot the difficulties encountered\nin producing sugar beet seed on a\n.commercial scalo has been tho clean\ning of the seed cheap onough to mako\nit practicable. This machlno, how\never, does the work effectively.\nThe possibility of cleaning the seed\ncheaply will give tho farmers of Utah\na better chance to enter tho field of\nsugar beet seod growing.\nCOLLEGE PRESIDENT\nCALLED TO REPRESENT\nTHE CHURCH SCHOOLS\nPresident Jensen Has. Gone East Where\nHe Will Get Information That Will\nMake B. Y. College Bigger and Bet\nter Standard Normal School.\nPresident C. N. Jensen received a\ncall from the Church Board of Edu\ncation to attend tho Convention ot\nthe Superintendents ot Schools to be\nheld at Richmond, Virginia. He will\nbo away for several weeks. Besides\nattending the Convention, the presi\ndent will spend some time visiting\ntho important Normal schools in the\ncast gathering oUhtehTcah'v be.\nused In tho developing of the Normal\nschool at the B. Y. C. Golng-with\nLEAH KLE8CHNA IN\nMOTION PICTURES\nLeah Kleschna is a penetrating\npsychological study. At the same\ntlmo Is intensely dramatic. It clearly\ndefines the awakening of tho girl's\nsoul and her final revolt against a\ncareer of crime yet tnere is never\nany recourse to the stale tricks of\nemotional acting. It is art conceal\ning art.\nMiss NUIson renders an Ideal Leah,\nnever exaggerating her appeal, but\nmaintaining a well balaned perform\nance. House Peters Is dignified and\nconvincing as Paul Sylvaln, a rolo ex\nceedingly difficult to portray. Hal\nClarendon gives a consistent and\nwell sustained performance as Klesch\nna and artistically suggests tho vary\ning emotions of that character. Alex\nander Qaden as Schram Is a notablo\nImpersonation.\nTho cast is perfect and tho tech\nnique of tho production far above tho\naverage which Is to bo expected from\ntho Famous Players.\nAt tho now Lyric tonight only.\nSAYS THAT MARTIN\nCASE HAS UPSET\nTHE CALENDAR\nEntire March Term Reserved Tor\nHearing Case Of Alleged\nBlackmailer By\nHowell\nOgden, Fob. 10. Inability to dcter\nmlno how long tho Martin caso will\noccupy tho tlmo of Judgo J. A. How\noil's division of tho district court\nand tho uncertainty ns to whothcr tho\ntrial will bo transferred from tho\ncourt led Judgo Howell to remark\nthat tho Martin caso has upset his\ncalendar. Tho Judgo occupied tho\nbench this morning, for tho first tlmo\nIn two weeks, to sot cases for tho\nMarch term\nMarch 12 was the dato decided on\nto begin tho caso of J. II. Martin,\ncharged with assault with intent to\ncommit murder and aB tho district\nPresident Jensen from Utah are Sup\nerintendent Cummlngs and President\nBrlmball. Tho collego feels honored\nin being able to have a representa\ntive on this Committee and knows\nthat President Jensen will ably repre\nsent tho schools ot tho church and\not the state, and will bo able to\nbring back a store ot experience and\nInformation that will make the B. Y.\nC.'a. bigger and better Standard Nor\nmal school.\nattorney said he expected the entire\nmonth would bo taken up with the\ncase, provided It Is tried hero he re\nserved most of the civil cases for\ntho April term. Tho dates for the\nhearings on the four indictment\niagalanst the alleged blackmailer woic\nnot set.\nThe date for tho trial of N. D.'Es\ntes, tho physician Indicted on tho\ncharge of Illegally prescribing for\nand selling narcotics was not set.\nJudgo Howell explained that in\ncaso tho motion for h change of von\nuo Is granted the April cases will bo\ntried in March.\nNEVADA DIVORCE\nLAW IS UPHELD\nBY .THE COURT\nReno, Nov., Feb. 10. By denying\nan application, for tho publication ot\nsummons in a dlvorco suit based on\nloss than a years resldenco Judgo\nMoran in the district court horo to\nday went on record as upholding the\nconstitutionality of Uio now divorce,\nlaw requlrng a yoar's resldenco ox\ncept where both parties llvo In tho\nstato. Counsel for tho applicant stat\ned they would apply to tho supromo\ncourt for a writ of mandate when\na final determination ot tho question\nwill bo had.\nAlfred Worthington, formerly of\nSan Matoo, California, sued Cecelia\nWorthington, a non-rosldent for dlv\norco alleging a resldenco ot less than\nsovon months. He applied for sum.\nmons by publication and tho question\ncatno up whothor tho low requiring\ntwolro months resldenco was consti\ntutional. Flvo leading lawyers appointed\nfriends ot tho court, defended tho\nconstitutionality of tho now act and\ntho lawyers representing plaintiff op\nposod It.\nOpposition wns based on tho claim\nthat tho title to tho act was defect! re\nand that tho act was class loglil.Htlon\nIn making dlfferont rules for differing\ncircumstances of resldenco.\nMore Modern H\nHomes For H\nLogan City H\nIt would seem that thero Is no end\nto tho number ot contemplated new\nhomes which will In all probability\nbo constructed In this city during the\ncoming summer. Mr. F. A. Dahlc,\ntho bungalow bulldor, reports that he\nhaB contracts for at loast a score ot\nmodern homes which will bo built\nduring the summer, and that no less\nthan fifty persons have made inquiry\nof him relative to terms and to tho\nclass of homes he Is building. Mr.\nDnhlo has Just made an arrangement\nWEBSTER PARTY\nWASHINGTON BIRTHDAY\nTho Wobsters of tho Collego are\nplanning a program to bo given at\ntho dovotlonal hour Friday. In tho\nevening tho patriotic spirit Is to\nbo continued in a Kappa nu party\ngiven In tho gymnnslum. Rivalry has\nalways run high with these two clubs\nas to tholr ability at entertaining.\nEach ono on Friday is putting forth\nextra efforts to mako Uio entertain\nment in its particular field on Fri\nday mako a good showing In compar\nison with that ot tho other club.\nClub Activity\nKappa-nu is adding extra furniture\nand furnishings to its room this week\nAlready the room has a cozy appear\nance, but an, extra effort la- going 'on\nthis week to mako it moro comfort\nable. Wobyea held a meeting In the din\ning room,.of the Mechanic Arts build\ning last evening. Prof. F. A. Hinck\nley lectured on Charities. The talk\nwas highly entertaining and Instruc\ntive and provoked considerable dis\ncussion. MisBes Sorenson and Bow\nen wero tho hostesses and served\nvery palatable refreshments after tho\ntalk.\nORGAN RECITAL\nInvitations aro out for tho Tracy\nCannon Organ Recital to bo given on\nwhereby any person who wishes a H\nhome built through the Logan Home\nBuilding Society, he is able to 'alio\ncare ot their needs at once. This H\ncan be dono by Mr. Dahle advanc- M\nIng the mono on tho home. A. per-\nson; must, however, on thia arrange- H\nmeat become a member ot the aocl- H\nety. With tho activity In tho building\nlino in other quarters, It would seam\nthat Logan, will have one ot tho big-\ngest building booms In tho history ot\nthe city during the season ot 1914.\nSaturday night under the auspices ot\nWobyea. After tho rocltal at tho tab-\ncrnnclo tho club and guests will have\ntho pleasuro of listening to tho sing- H\ning of a number of Mr. Cannon's\nlyrics. Mrs. Ethel J. Clayton will H\nsing theso lyrics. For tho singing H\nand entertainment tho Wobyea will\nuso tho club rooms of tho Commercial\nBoosters. PPPH\nMELLEN TO BE TRIED iH\nFOR MANSLAUGHTER\nIndictments Against Other New H\nHaven Officials, Past and' H\nAre H\nPPPPJ\nBridgeport, Conn., Feb. 16. H\nState's JVttoraoy Judson today quash- 'LsH\ned the manslaughter indictments fH\nagainst five officials ot the New York\nNew Haven Hartford' railroad, but H\nrefused to quash, tho indictment H\nagainst former President Charles W.\nMollen. The wreck occurred at West H\nport, Conn., October 3, 1913, in H\nwhich sevon persons wore killed. H\nOfficials of the road past and\npresent, against whom indictments H\nwere quashod aro: C. H. McHenry\nand Henry J. Horn, former vice pros H\nIdents; B. R. Pollock, former gen- JH\noral manager; C. N. Woodward, H\ngeneral superintendent and Laurence\nJ. Carmalt, former engineer of main- H\ntonanco and ways. PjJH\nFARMERS MEETING I\nAT POCATELLO I\nWas a Great Gathering Of Tillers Of\nthe Soil. Organization Is on\na Firm Footing\nSocrotary John A. Israelson of Hy\nrum has sent in tho following report\nof tho Farmers convention Hold in\nPocatolio on Friday and Saturday,\nFobruary 13 and li.\nTho opening meeting of tho con\nvention was called to order ut 10.., a.\nm. on Friday morning by President\nA. Y. Satterfield. Tho first session\nwas very well attended and delegates\nfrom various county unions continued\ncoming in on overy train. Speakors\ntold of tho great amount ot good that\nhad como to mombors through tholr\norganized effort. Stako Secretary O.\nB. Scott reported having dono near\nly halt n million dollars worth of\nbusiness during tho past year. Ho\nsaid that tho prlco paid farmers for\ntholr wheat crop had been from 10\nto 15 cents hotter per hundred pounds\nthan local markets had offerod, Tho\npotato growors had shipped aovoral\ncar loads of potatoes through tho\noffice and that bther crops wero han\ndled to cdvantago for members. Sav\nings wore mado by purchasing sacks\ntwine, lumber, coal and machinery in\nlargo assortmonts.\nAt 5:30 on Friday night a banquet B\nwas given at which ono hundred and IH\nthirty-seven tillers of tho soil wore Jjpj\nsorvod, four states represented, four- H\nteen countlos and 10,000 farmers. H\nCacho county sent thirteen delegates H\n!from tho various locals. Short H\nspeeches were mado and a ploasant iH\novcnlng etfJoj'eU by all. JH\nTho Saturday sessions wero dovot- H\ned mostly to business. Officers wero i\neloctcd for tho ensuing year. Resolu- iJH\ntlons passed. Talks mado by men H\nfrom oast and west representing bag JJJ\nmanufacturers, Implement compan- i\nles, lumber wholesalers, wire factor- H\nles and wagon and buggy compan- .fH\nles. An order was placed for ton JH\ncar loads, half a million bags, another .-ifS\nfor several cars of lumber, machln- iH\ncry, etc. Four building lots woro pur- M\nchased Ijolnlng tho railroad and M\nmaterials ordorcd for constructing M\nwarehouses. A committee represent- M\nIng tho Southern Idaho Producers' jH\nAssociation mot and rocolved coudt- lM\ntlons for federating with tho Farmors M\nSociety ot Equity. Delegates were H\neloctcd to attend tho next national M\nconvontlon, Saturday ovenlng the JH\nconvention closed and was pronounc- aH\ned tho largest mooting ot farmors ov- H\nor held In tho mountain states.. JH\n:9","height":"25176","width":"17624"}}
